'<h2>web scraping using JavaScript on the browser side</h2>\n<center><div id="browsersidetoc" class="toc"><a href="#browsersidetopic-0" target="_self">Methods for Browser-Side Web Scraping</a><br><a href="#browsersidetopic-1" target="_self">Limitations of Browser-Side Scraping</a><br><a href="#browsersidetopic-2" target="_self">Better Alternatives for Heavy Scraping</a><br><a href="#browsersidetopic-3" target="_self">Conclusion</a><br></div></center><br><br>\n\nwith some limitations.\nHere’s how it works and what you need to consider:\n<o id="browsersidetopic-0">Methods for Browser-Side Web Scraping</o>\n1. <lg>Using `fetch()` + DOM Parsing (for Same-Origin or CORS-Enabled Sites)</lg>\n- Fetch HTML content and parse it using the DOM.\n- Example:\n  fetch(\'https://example.com\')\n   .then(response =&gt; response.text())\n   .then(html =&gt; {\n    const parser = new DOMParser();\n    const doc = parser.parseFromString(html, \'text/html\');\n    const titles = doc.querySelectorAll(\'h1\');\n    titles.forEach(title =&gt; console.log(title.textContent));\n   })\n   .catch(error =&gt; console.error(\'Error:\', error));\n- <lg>Limitation:</lg> Works only if the target site allows <lg>CORS</lg> (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing), which most external sites block.\n\n2. <lg>Using Browser Extensions (Chrome/Firefox)</lg>\n- Extensions can bypass CORS restrictions (with proper permissions).\n- Example (Chrome extension using `chrome.scripting` or `content scripts`).\n\n3. <lg>Injecting Scripts via DevTools (Manual Scraping)</lg>\n- Open DevTools (`F12`), go to the <lg>Console</lg>, and run JavaScript to extract data:\n  const data = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll(\'.post\')).map(el =&gt; ({\n   title: el.querySelector(\'h2\').innerText,\n   url: el.querySelector(\'a\').href\n  }));\n  console.log(data);\n- You can then copy the output manually.\n\n4. <lg>Bookmarklet (Mini JavaScript Snippet)</lg>\n- Save a JavaScript snippet as a bookmark to scrape the current page:\n  javascript:(function() {\n   const text = document.body.innerText;\n   prompt("Page Text:", text);\n  })();\n\n5. <lg>Proxy Server (to Avoid CORS)</lg>\n- If you control a backend, you can fetch data via your server (which bypasses CORS) and then retrieve it in the browser.\n<o id="browsersidetopic-1">Limitations of Browser-Side Scraping</o>\n- <lg>CORS Restrictions:</lg> Most websites block cross-origin requests.\n- <lg>Dynamic Content:</lg> Some sites load data via JavaScript (SPAs like React/Angular), requiring tools like <lg>Puppeteer</lg> (which runs in Node.js, not the browser).\n- <lg>Legal &amp; Ethical Issues:</lg> Many sites prohibit scraping in their <lg>Terms of Service</lg>.\n- <lg>Rate Limiting/IP Blocking:</lg> Excessive requests may get you blocked.\n<o id="browsersidetopic-2">Better Alternatives for Heavy Scraping</o>\n1. <lg>Backend Scraping (Node.js + Puppeteer/Cheerio)</lg>\n   const puppeteer = require(\'puppeteer\');\n   (async () =&gt; {\n  const browser = await puppeteer.launch();\n  const page = await browser.newPage();\n  await page.goto(\'https://example.com\');\n  const data = await page.evaluate(() =&gt; document.body.innerText);\n  console.log(data);\n  await browser.close();\n   })();\n 2. <lg>API-Based Scraping Services</lg> (e.g., ScrapingBee, Apify)\n<o id="browsersidetopic-3">Conclusion</o>\n- <lg>For simple scraping on the same domain or CORS-allowed sites</lg>, browser-side JS works.\n- <lg>For external sites</lg>, use a backend (Node.js + Puppeteer) or a browser extension.\n- <lg>For large-scale scraping</lg>, consider a dedicated scraping tool/service.\n',
