'<h2>To run another Node.js script from a main Node.js script</h2>\nand capture its output until the child script finishes, you can use the `child_process` module to spawn a new process.\nHere\'s an example of how you can achieve this:\n\n1. <lg>Main Node.js Script (`mainScript.js`)</lg>:\n const { spawn } = require(\'child_process\');\n // Run the child script\n const childProcess = spawn(\'node\', [\'childScript.js\']);\n\n // Listen for the \'data\' event to capture the output of the child script\n childProcess.stdout.on(\'data\', (data) => {\n   console.log(data.toString());\n });\n\n // Listen for the \'close\' event to know when the child process has finished\n childProcess.on(\'close\', (code) => {\n   console.log(`Child process finished with code ${code}`);\n   // Code to execute after the child process has completed\n });\n\n2. <lg>Child Node.js Script (`childScript.js`)</lg>:\n This is the script that you want to run and capture the output from.\n\n // Code in childScript.js\n console.log(\'Child script is running...\');\n // Any other code you want to execute in the child script\n\n3. <lg>How It Works</lg>:\n - The main script uses `child_process.spawn()` to run the child script (`childScript.js`) as a separate Node.js process.\n - The output of the child script is captured by listening to the `data` event on the `stdout` stream of the child process.\n - The `close` event is used to know when the child process has finished running.\n\nWhen you run the main script (`mainScript.js`) using `node mainScript.js`, it will execute the child script (`childScript.js`) and display the output of the child script until it finishes.\nThe main script will continue running after the child process has completed.\nIf the child script running as a separate process requires user input, you can still interact with it from the main Node.js script using `child.stdin.write()` to provide input to the child script.\nHere\'s an example illustrating how you can achieve this:\n\n1. <lg>Main Node.js Script (`mainScript.js`)</lg>:\n const { spawn } = require(\'child_process\');\n \n // Run the child script\n const childProcess = spawn(\'node\', [\'childScript.js\'], { stdio: [\'pipe\', \'pipe\', \'pipe\'] });\n\n // Listen for data from the child script\n childProcess.stdout.on(\'data\', (data) => {\n   console.log(data.toString());\n });\n\n // Provide input to the child script\n childProcess.stdin.write(\'User input from main script\n\');\n\n // Handle user input to provide to the child script\n process.stdin.on(\'data\', (data) => {\n   childProcess.stdin.write(data);\n });\n\n // Listen for the \'close\' event\n childProcess.on(\'close\', (code) => {\n   console.log(`Child process finished with code ${code}`);\n });\n\n2. <lg>Child Node.js Script (`childScript.js`)</lg>:\n\n This is the script that requires user input.\n process.stdin.on(\'data\', (data) => {\n   console.log(`Received input in child script: ${data.toString()}`);\n });\n\n console.log(\'Child script is running...\');\n\n3. <lg>How It Works</lg>:\n - The main script spawns the child script as a separate process with communication pipes enabled for `stdin`, `stdout`, and `stderr`.\n - User input can be provided to the child script from the main script using `childProcess.stdin.write()`.\n - The child script listens for user input using `process.stdin.on(\'data\', ...)`.\n - When the child script requests input, the main script can provide it through `childProcess.stdin.write()`.\n\nWhen you run the main script (`mainScript.js`), it will communicate with the child script (`childScript.js`) and allow for interaction by providing input from the main script to the child script.\n\nIt is possible to run multiple child scripts from a main Node.js script and interact with each child script independently by managing their input and output streams individually.\nHere\'s an example demonstrating how you can run multiple child scripts and interact with each of them:\n\n1. <lg>Main Node.js Script (`mainScript.js`)</lg>:\n const { spawn } = require(\'child_process\');\n\n // Function to start a child process\n function startChildScript(scriptName) {\n   const childProcess = spawn(\'node\', [scriptName], { stdio: [\'pipe\', \'pipe\', \'pipe\'] });\n\n   // Listen for data from the child script\n   childProcess.stdout.on(\'data\', (data) => {\n     console.log(`${scriptName}: ${data.toString()}`);\n   });\n\n   // Provide input to the child script\n   childProcess.stdin.write(\'User input from main script\n\');\n\n   // Handle user input to provide to the child script\n   process.stdin.on(\'data\', (data) => {\n     childProcess.stdin.write(data);\n   });\n\n   // Listen for the \'close\' event\n   childProcess.on(\'close\', (code) => {\n     console.log(`${scriptName}: Child process finished with code ${code}`);\n   });\n }\n\n // Start multiple child scripts\n startChildScript(\'childScript1.js\');\n startChildScript(\'childScript2.js\');\n\n2. <lg>Child Node.js Scripts (`childScript1.js`, `childScript2.js`, etc.)</lg>:\n\n These are the scripts that you want to run as child processes. You can have multiple child scripts.\n\n3. <lg>How It Works</lg>:\n - The `startChildScript()` function is used to spawn a child process for each child script.\n - Each child process has its own input and output streams, allowing interaction with each child script independently.\n - User input can be provided to each child script from the main script.\n - The child scripts can communicate with the main script through their standard input and output streams.\n\nWhen you run the main script (`mainScript.js`), it will start multiple child scripts and manage interactions with each of them independently, providing input and handling output for each child script separately.',
