'<h2>Creating HTML Tables in R</h2>\nThere are several ways to create HTML tables from R data.\nHere are the main methods:\n<h3>1. Using `knitr::kable()`</h3>library(knitr)\n# Create a data frame\nmy_data <- data.frame(\n  Name = c("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie"),\n  Age = c(25, 30, 35),\n  Score = c(88, 92, 85)\n)\n# Generate HTML table\nkable(my_data, format = "html")\n<h3>2. Using the `DT` package (interactive tables)</h3>library(DT)\ndatatable(my_data)\n<h3>3. Using the `htmlTable` package</h3>library(htmlTable)\nhtmlTable(my_data)\n<h3>4. Using `xtable`</h3>library(xtable)\nprint(xtable(my_data), type = "html")\n<h3>5. Using `flextable`</h3>library(flextable)\nflextable(my_data) %>% htmltools_value()\n<h3>Saving to a file</h3>To save the HTML table to a file:\n# Using kable\nwriteLines(kable(my_data, format = "html"), "table.html")\n\n# Using htmlTable\nwriteLines(htmlTable(my_data), "table.html")\n<h3>Customizing the table</h3>Most packages allow customization:\n# With kable\nkable(my_data, format = "html", \n  caption = "My Table", \n  align = c("l", "c", "r"),\n  table.attr = \'class="table table-striped"\')\n\n`kable` is great for simple tables in R Markdown, `DT` for interactive tables, and `flextable` for highly customizable tables.\n',
'<h2>小苏打和嫩肉粉</h2>\n<h3>1. 小苏打（食用碱）</h3>- <lg>成分</lg>：化学名 <lg>碳酸氢钠（NaHCO₃）</lg>，弱碱性。  \n- <lg>嫩肉原理</lg>：  \n - 碱性环境能破坏肉类纤维结构，使蛋白质松弛，锁住水分，从而达到嫩化效果。  \n - 尤其适合 <lg>牛肉、鸡胸肉</lg> 等容易柴的肉类。  \n- <lg>特点</lg>：  \n - <lg>需控制用量</lg>（一般肉重的0.5%~1%），过量会有苦味和涩感。  \n - 需静置15~20分钟，之后冲洗干净再烹饪（避免碱味残留）。  \n- <lg>常见用途</lg>：粤式“松肉粉”主要成分就是小苏打，也用于腌制牛肉片、虾仁等。\n\n<h3>2. 嫩肉粉</h3>- <lg>成分</lg>：  \n - 主要含 <lg>蛋白酶（如木瓜蛋白酶、菠萝蛋白酶）</lg>，可能添加少量淀粉、磷酸盐等。  \n- <lg>嫩肉原理</lg>：  \n - 蛋白酶分解肉类中的胶原蛋白和纤维，直接软化肉质，对 <lg>老肉、筋多的部位</lg>（如牛腩、猪蹄）效果显著。  \n- <lg>特点</lg>：  \n - 用量更灵活（按说明书），无需冲洗，腌制后直接烹饪。  \n - 作用温和，不易产生异味，但过度使用会导致肉质变“粉”。  \n\n<h3>3. 两者的关联与区别</h3>对比项 : 作用方式 \n小苏打 : 化学嫩化（碱性破坏） \n嫩肉粉 : 生物酶解（蛋白酶分解） \n\n对比项 : 适用肉类 \n小苏打 : 瘦肉（牛肉、鸡胸） \n嫩肉粉 : 筋多或老肉（牛腩、猪蹄） \n\n对比项 : 用量控制 \n小苏打 : 严格，过量发苦 \n嫩肉粉 : 较宽松，但过量会软烂 \n\n对比项 : 是否需要冲洗 \n小苏打 : 通常需要 \n嫩肉粉 : 不需要 \n\n对比项 : 风味影响 \n小苏打 : 可能残留碱味 \n嫩肉粉 : 几乎无味 \n\n<h3>4. 注意事项</h3>- <lg>小苏打</lg>：  \n - 适合快炒类菜肴（如滑蛋牛肉），腌制后需冲洗。  \n - 不可与醋或酸性调料同时使用（会中和失效）。  \n- <lg>嫩肉粉</lg>：  \n - 避免长时间腌制（超过1小时可能导致肉质过软）。  \n - 天然蛋白酶（如木瓜汁）可替代部分化学嫩肉粉。  \n\n<h3>5. 替代方案</h3>- 如果追求天然嫩化，可用 <lg>猕猴桃汁、菠萝汁</lg>（含天然蛋白酶）腌制肉类，但需控制时间（约15分钟）。  \n总结：小苏打通过化学方式嫩肉，适合短时间处理；嫩肉粉通过生物酶解，适合难熟的部位，两者可根据食材和需求选择或组合使用（如先用小苏打嫩化，再用蛋白酶进一步软化）。\n',
'<h2>Convert a dataframe in R into a JavaScript object</h2>\n1. <o>Convert Dataframe to JSON</o>:\n Use the `jsonlite` package in R to convert the dataframe to JSON format.\n\n2. <o>Write JSON Data to a File</o>:\n Write the JSON data to a JavaScript file that can be included in your HTML file.\n\n<lg>Example</lg>:\n1. <o>Install and Load the `jsonlite` Package</o>:\n If you haven\'t installed the `jsonlite` package yet, you can do so using the following command:\n\n install.packages("jsonlite")\n library(jsonlite)\n2. <o>Create a Sample Data Frame</o>:\n # Sample data frame\n df <- data.frame(\n   Name = c("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie"),\n   Age = c(25, 30, 35),\n   Score = c(80, 85, 90)\n )\n3. <o>Convert Dataframe to JSON</o>:\n Convert the dataframe to JSON format using the `toJSON()` function from the `jsonlite` package:\n\n # Convert dataframe to JSON\n json_data <- toJSON(df, pretty = TRUE)\n4. <o>Write JSON Data to a JavaScript File</o>:\n # Write JSON data to a JavaScript file\n writeLines(paste("var data =", json_data, ";"), "data.js")\n\n This code will write the JSON data to a file named `data.js` with the JavaScript variable `data` containing the JSON object.\n\n5. <o>Create an HTML File</o>:\n &lt;html>\n &lt;head>\n   &lt;script src="data.js">&lt;/script>\n &lt;/head>\n &lt;body>\n   &lt;script>\n   console.log(data); // Access the JSON data in the data variable\n   &lt;/script>\n &lt;/body>\n &lt;/html>\n',
'<h2>Convert the JSON data into a sortable HTML table</h2>\n1. <lg>Include Required Libraries</lg>:\n&lt;html>\n&lt;head>\n  &lt;link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="https://cdn.datatables.net/1.10.25/css/jquery.dataTables.min.css">\n&lt;/head>\n&lt;body>\n  &lt;table id="myTable" class="display">\n    &lt;!-- Table content will be populated using JavaScript -->\n  &lt;/table>\n  &lt;script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js">&lt;/script>\n  &lt;script src="https://cdn.datatables.net/1.10.25/js/jquery.dataTables.min.js">&lt;/script>\n  &lt;script src="data.js">&lt;/script>\n&lt;/body>\n&lt;/html>\n\n2. <lg>Parse JSON Data and Populate Table</lg>:\n&lt;script>\n $(document).ready(function() {\n  // Parse the JSON data from data.js\n  $.getJSON("data.js", function(data) {\n   // Populate the table with the JSON data\n   $(\'#myTable\').DataTable({\n    data: data,\n    columns: [\n     { data: \'Name\' },\n     { data: \'Age\' },\n     { data: \'Score\' }\n    ]\n   });\n  });\n });\n&lt;/script>\n\n3. <lg>Initialize the DataTable</lg>:\nIn the script above, `$(\'#myTable\').DataTable()` initializes the DataTable on the table with the id `myTable`. The `data` parameter is used to provide the JSON data, and `columns` specify which data fields to display in each column.\n',
'<h2>generate semantic HTML table using only base R</h2>\n# loop DataFrame to obtain database\nouttable <<- rbind(outtable, data.frame(codeStr, avgAmt, firstMinuteAmt, firstMinuteAmtRatio, lastMinuteAmt, lastMinuteAmtRatio))\n\n# Generate HTML table with headers, note the sortable\nhtml_table <- c(\n  "<table class="sortable">",\n  paste0("<tr><th>", paste(names(df), collapse = "</th><th>"), "</th></tr>"),\n  apply(df, 1, function(row) paste0("<tr><td>", paste(row, collapse = "</td><td>"), "</td></tr>")),\n  "</table>"\n)\n\n# convert to text\ntabletxt = capture.output(cat(html_table, sep = "\n"))\n',
'<h2>To calculate the last WMA value by r</h2>\nand check the following code for improvements\n# calculate the WMA value\ncalcWAve = function(myArray) {\n  sum = 0\n  for( i in 1:length(myArray) ) {sum = sum + myArray[i] * i;}\n  return (sum / ((1 + length(myArray))*length(myArray)/2))\n}\n\n# improved version\ncalcWMA <- function(x) {\n  if (length(x) == 0) return(NA)\n  # Calculate weights (1, 2, ..., n)\n  weights <- 1:length(x)\n  # Compute weighted sum and normalize by sum of weights\n  weighted_sum <- sum(x * weights)\n  sum_weights <- sum(weights)\n  # Return WMA\n  return(weighted_sum / sum_weights)\n}\n\nTo improve the code, consider the following points:\nEfficiency: Use vectorized operations instead of for loop.\nVariable Name: Avoid using sum as a variable name (it\'s a built-in function).\nReadability: Add comments to explain the calculation.\nError Handling: Consider checking for empty inputs.\n',
